1. Find the last occurrence of a space character from the right end of the array. Let's call this index `end`.
2. Starting from the last index of the array (`s.length() - 1`), move towards the left and swap the current character with the character at index `end`. Decrement `end` after each swap to move towards the previous space character.
3. After all the words have been reversed within themselves, reverse the entire string by swapping the first and last characters, and then reverse each word again.

Here's the code to implement the above steps:

```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <vector>
#include <string>

void reverseWords(char* s, int length) {
    int start = 0; // index of the first non-space character in the current word
    int end = length - 1; // index of the last non-space character in the current word

    // reverse each word
    while (start < length && end >= 0) {
        if (s[start] == ' ') {
            start++; // move to the next word
        } else {
            std::swap(s[start], s[end]); // swap the current character with the corresponding character at the end of the word
            start++; // move to the next non-space character in the word
            end--; // move towards the previous space character
        }
    }

    // reverse the entire string
    std::reverse(s, s + length);

    // reverse each word again (since we swapped the first and last characters of each word during the first reversal)
    for (int i = 0; i < length; i += std::strlen(s + i) + 1) {
        std::reverse(s + i, s + i + std::strlen(s + i));
    }
}

